                  </rs>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460817-name-895" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-895" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-895" type="surname" value="ADOLPHUS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-895" type="given" value="LEWIS"></interp>LEWIS ADOLPHUS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the service of Mr. Moses, of the Minories. The prisoner was one of our tailors—when the workmen bring in the whole of their work they receive a ticket, which is taken to the clerk, and he pays them—this ticket is an order for money, and purports to be written by Mr. Pengelly—it is forged.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Have you any of the tickets which I have received on former occasions of Mr. Pengelly's writing? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460817-name-896" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-896" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-896" type="surname" value="PENGELLY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-896" type="given" value="JAMES PANCOMBE"></interp>JAMES PANCOMBE PENGELLY</persName>
                  </hi>. This ticket is like my handwriting, but it is not mine—it is a forged order.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Have you not given persons tickets twice in the week? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Never; I have never been mistaken and given a person a ticket twice.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460817-name-897" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-897" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-897" type="surname" value="ORANGE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-897" type="given" value="CHARLOTTE"></interp>CHARLOTTE ORANGE</persName>
                  </hi>. I work for Mr. Fredericks, who is an assistant of the prisoner. On Saturday night the prisoner sent me with this ticket—I went, and Mr. Forster gave me the 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460817-name-898" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-898" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-898" type="surname" value="FORSTER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-898" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN FORSTER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am pay-clerk to Mr. Moses. I paid the 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. to the girl, believing this order to be written by Pengelly.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Had you any suspicion of it not being Mr. Pengelly writing? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not the slightest, but I have now—it is not such a free hand.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I have received nothing but what was owing to me; I received the ticket from Mr. Pengelly on Saturday night, and kept it to provide for myself, as we are so often kept without our money.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460817-name-899" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-899" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-899" type="surname" value="FORSTER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-899" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN FORSTER</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> I did not owe him any money—by receifinf the 10. he has overdrawn his account—the ticket merely says, "pay"—"already entered in the book How much is to be paid—the prisoner was called up—I looked at the book, and found I had paid him—he said I had not and, to make my statement good I searched and found the ticket, which exonerated me—if I had not found it I should have had to pay him again—I had go "paid" in the book.</p>
